Looking at the code fragments, I can see that the Hexi library provides `conditional_reverse` for compile-time endianness conversion. For the runtime version, I'll need to implement the logic based on the pattern shown in `conditional_reverse_inplace`.

Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/endian.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <bit>

template<std::endian from, std::endian to, typename T>
T convert_endianness(T value) {
    return hexi::conditional_reverse<from, to>(value);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_endianness_runtime(T value, std::endian from, std::endian to) {
    if (from == to) {
        return value;
    }

    // Need to swap bytes when endianness differs
    if constexpr(std::is_same_v<T, float>) {
        return std::bit_cast<T>(std::byteswap(std::bit_cast<std::uint32_t>(value)));
    } else if constexpr(std::is_same_v<T, double>) {
        return std::bit_cast<T>(std::byteswap(std::bit_cast<std::uint64_t>(value)));
    } else {
        return std::byteswap(value);
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **`convert_endianness`**: This function uses compile-time template parameters for endianness, so it delegates to Hexi's `conditional_reverse` function which handles the conversion efficiently at compile time.

2. **`convert_endianness_runtime`**: Since the endianness is determined at runtime, this function:
   - First checks if conversion is needed (when `from == to`, no conversion is required)
   - For floating-point types (`float` and `double`), it uses `std::bit_cast` to convert to an integer type, performs byte swap, then converts back
   - For integral types, it directly uses `std::byteswap`

